/div></div><div class="chev">▸</div></div><div class="body"><h4>Learning objectives</h4><ul><li>Understand what an organization and its culture are, and how culture can be managed.</li><li>Learn and practice how to diagnose, design and deploy organizational change.</li><li>Identify and improve how we lead people through change.</li></ul><h4>Key concepts (from course materials)</h4><ul><li><b>What an organization is</b> — a collective of individuals/teams pursuing shared goals; sets strategies (management models); has structure, processes &amp; power distribution; tacit &amp; explicit norms; achieves its purpose <i>through culture</i>.</li><li><b>What culture is</b> — observable patterns of beliefs &amp; behaviors; 'what happens when managers leave the room'; sense-making; a carrier of meaning; a social control system; shaped by incentives and societal context.</li><li><b>Schein's three levels</b> — Artifacts; Espoused Values; Basic Underlying Assumptions.</li><li><b>Organizational Culture Components</b> — Leader at the center, surrounded by Structure, People &amp; Values, all within Context.</li><li><b>Culture types (Competing Values)</b> — Clan, Adhocracy, Hierarchy, Market.</li><li><b>Hofstede's 6 dimensions</b> &amp; the <b>functions of culture</b> (identity; real drivers; what is acceptable; commitment, engagement &amp; accountability).</li></ul><h4>Prep questions to think through</h4><ul><li>Map an organization you know onto Schein's three levels.</li><li>Which of the four culture types best describes it, and why?</li></ul></div></div><div class="theme-band"><span>Culture &amp; Change</span><div class="bar"></div></div><div class="card" data-n="3"><div class="head" onclick="SG.toggle(3)"><div class="num">3</div><div class="titles"><div class="t">Culture and Change</div><div class="d">Session 3 · Columbia's Final Mission (multimedia case)</div></div><div class="chev">▸</div></div><div class="body"><h4>Learning objectives</h4><ul><li>Connect culture diagnosis to 