<h2 class="sec">Hofstede's Six Cultural Dimensions</h2>
<div class="note"><ul>
<li><b>Distance to Power</b> — degree to which less powerful members accept unequal power distribution.</li>
<li><b>Long-term vs. Short-term</b> — how much people link present actions to future outcomes.</li>
<li><b>Uncertainty Avoidance</b> — society's tolerance for ambiguity.</li>
<li><b>Success &amp; Achievement vs. Well-being &amp; Collaboration</b> — achievement valued over cooperation, or not.</li>
<li><b>Individualism vs. Collectivism</b> — degree to which society is integrated into groups.</li>
<li><b>Restraint vs. Indulgence</b> — allowing gratification related to enjoying life and having fun.</li>
</ul></div>

<h2 class="sec">How Culture is Created, Maintained &amp; Learned</h2>
<div class="note"><ul>
<li><b>Selection</b> (hiring for fit) and <b>Socialization</b> (adapting to the prevailing culture).</li>
<li>Maintained through <b>People Selection</b>, <b>Top Management Example</b>, and <b>Socialization</b>.</li>
<li><b>Functions of culture:</b> provides identity; embodies the real drivers of the organization; determines which beliefs/behaviors are acceptable; enables commitment, engagement and accountability.</li>
</ul></div>
</section>
 <section class="view" id="view-glossary"><h2 class="sec">Glossary (terms from the course)</h2><dl class="glossary"><dt>Artifacts</dt><dd>Visible level of culture: architecture, technology, layout, dress and behaviors; easy to observe, hard to interpret.</dd><dt>Espoused values</dt><dd>The stated reasons/rationalizations for how members behave.</dd><dt>Basic underlying assumptions</dt><dd>Taken-for-granted beliefs about truth, human nature, time and space.</dd><dt>Sense-making</dt><dd>Culture viewed as a process by which members interpret reality and act accordingly.</dd><dt>Social control system</dt><dd>Culture's role in guiding behavior 'when managers leave the room.'</dd><dt>Selection</dt><dd>Creating/maintaining culture by hiring people who fit it.</dd><dt>Socialization</dt><dd>Creating/maintaining culture by having members adapt to the prevailing culture.</dd><dt>Exploration vs. exploitation</dt><dd>Trade-off where strong cultures favor exploitation and may struggle in volatile environments.</dd><dt>Cultural iceberg</dt><dd>Model contrasting visible culture (above water) with invisible beliefs/assumptions (below).</dd><dt>Competing Values types</dt><dd>Clan, Adhocracy, Hierarchy, Market — positioned on internal/external and flexibility/control axes.</dd><dt>Accepted risk</dt><dd>Normalization of risk through cultural assumptions (Columbia/Challenger lesson).</dd></dl></section>
